data.content:
This code **does not use `Thread.Abort`**, so there's no `Thread.Abort` migration issue here. It uses `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep` — all of which remain supported in .NET 8.

That said, this pattern is outdated. The modern .NET 8 equivalent uses `Parallel.ForEach` or `Task`:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public void RunBatch(List<WorkItem> items)
    {
        Parallel.ForEach(items, item =>
        {
            Thread.Sleep(100); // or await Task.Delay(100) if async
            item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
        });
    }
}
```

**Key `Thread.Abort` migration notes** (for when you do encounter it):

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 Replacement |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — **removed** |
| Cancellation via abort | Use `CancellationToken` with cooperative cancellation |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | No longer needed |

**Pattern to adopt:**
```csharp
// Pass CancellationToken into work methods
private void Process(WorkItem item, CancellationToken ct)
{
    ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
    item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
}
```

